            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--Dios Soteros Hieronos. Hugely difficult in interpretation! Employed in Serrati's thesis, p.166, as part of argument re ruler cult of Hieron (and see now Historia). Note SEG 34.961, which is another small domestic altar, with the inscr. DIOS, originally publ'd by Manganaro in CronASA 16 (1977 [1985]), p.156 n.43. The letters are very nasty - scratched rather than cut, and very uneven. The altar has suffered some damage to its upper part. It's v. small (less than 20cm). BE 1971 is report of Habicht's second edition, including the discussion of this inscr. Viz. Habicht, Chr. 1970 (2nd ed.). Gottmenschentum und griechische Städte (Munich), pp.259-62: part of the ‘Nachtrag’ which constitutes the rev’d ed. Of this vol. (1st ed. 1956); an addition to the listings of pt. 1, being no.54, ‘Der Kult Hierons II.in Syrakus’. This is a discussion of BE 1953.282. In essence, the nature of the object makes it clearly of a private context, not a state or royal monument. There is no other evidence for the cult. The inscr. Clearly assmiliates Hieron to Zeus Soter (without necessarily literally identifying the two). It’s not a true votive, since there’s a lack of a) dative recipient, b) name of dedicant, but rather a statement of cult / veneration vel sim. There are plenty of parallels in a private context from the C3-2 BC eastern Med. Private context of course presumes some form of state cult and/or state instruction (for which again Ptolemaic and Asia Minor parallels). H stresses the Egyptian / Ptolemaic links and parallels. Discussion of cult and parallels in Manganaro 1977, for which note also p.153 with vase graffito evidence for Zeus Soter cult in Hieronian Syracuse, and also p.149ff for discussion of double genetive dedications, although M does not then pick this up in relation to this document. In p.156 n.43 M notes e.g. the Morgantina or Akrae altar with 'Dios'--></p>
            </div>
